5":"1165","1264":"1264","Feb 1219":"februar 1219","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1191–1247":"1191–1247","1224–1264":"1224–1264","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","Feb 1219":"februari 1219","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England"},"en":{"1191–1247":"1191–1247","1224–1264":"1224–1264","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","Feb 1219":"February 1219","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":24,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":33,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Herbert DePyn IV was born in 1191, in Upton Pyne, Devon, England as the son of Herbert III DePyn. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1247, in Somerset, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1191–1247":"1191–1247","1224–1264":"1224–1264","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","Feb 1219":"veebruar 1219","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1191–1247":"1191–1247","1224–1264":"1224–1264